3. Cluster upgrade: https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/administer-cluster/kubeadm/kubeadm-upgrade/
We are using kubeadm here.

Before upgrading the cluster, we need to upgrade the kubeadm. Then upgrade the master node and node on the worker nodes.

Here in this case kubelet is running the controlplane components as pod on the master nodes.

So, After upgrading the master node using kubeadm. Upgrade kubelet and worker nodes as one by one.


Note: Whenever we upgrade the master node, it doesn't mean the pods on the worker node will get impacted but the creation of new pods or replicas
won't work due to the components on the master node is down.


# kubectl get nodes
Upgrade from v1.28 to v1.29

Step 1: https://kubernetes.io/blog/2023/08/15/pkgs-k8s-io-introduction/

Install packages on each node, check the repositories for the package.
Also check the OS version using command # cat /etc/*release*
Check Pretty_Name=ubuntu

echo "deb [signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/kubernetes-apt-keyring.gpg] https://pkgs.k8s.io/core:/stable:/v1.29/deb/ /" | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/kubernetes.list

curl -fsSL https://pkgs.k8s.io/core:/stable:/v1.29/deb/Release.key | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /etc/apt/keyrings/kubernetes-apt-keyring.gpg

Step 2:
# Find the latest 1.29 version in the list.
# It should look like 1.29.x-*, where x is the latest patch.
sudo apt update
sudo apt-cache madison kubeadm

Step 3: kubeadm with cluster will be upgraded
Upgrade control plane
# replace x in 1.29.x-* with the latest patch version
sudo apt-mark unhold kubeadm && \
sudo apt-get update && sudo apt-get install -y kubeadm='1.29.x-*' && \
sudo apt-mark hold kubeadm

